      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/X_Corp.",
      "suggested_edit": "Add to the 'Litigation and regulatory scrutiny' subsection: In December 2025, X terminated the European Commission’s Ad Account after the EU paid to promote an announcement using a deceptive trick that disguised a link as a video to artificially increase reach, while simultaneously fining X for deceptive practices. X highlighted the irony, noting the EU logged into a dormant ad account to exploit X's Ad Composer.",
      "original_text": "Regulators in the European Union have scrutinized X under the Digital Services Act (DSA) since December 2023, probing failures in risk assessment, disinformation mitigation, and illegal content dissemination. [161] The European Commission requested internal algorithm documents in January 2025 and prepared significant penalties by April 2025 for alleged DSA breaches, including inadequate handling of illicit material and transparency deficits. [162] [163] However, one probe stalled in July 2025 amid U.S.-EU trade negotiations. [164]"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Southwest_Airlines",
      "suggested_edit": "Update the regulatory issues section: Following the 2022 holiday meltdown and January 2025 DOT lawsuit for chronic delays, in December 2025, President Trump waived the remaining fines against Southwest Airlines and shut down the government suit for 'chronically delayed flights,' with the announcement from the Transportation Department under former airline lobbyist Secretary Sean Duffy.",
      "original_text": "Post-recovery challenges included the 2022 holiday operational meltdown, which canceled over 16,000 flights, incurred a $140 million FAA fine, and exposed technology vulnerabilities, contributing to ongoing capacity constraints and a fourth-quarter 2023 net loss of $219 million. In January 2025, DOT filed a lawsuit against Southwest alleging chronic delays on two routes (Las Vegas to San Diego and Orlando to Aruba) exceeding federal tarmac delay rules, seeking civil penalties up to $37,377 per violation without admitting liability by the airline."
    },
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Donald_Trump",
      "suggested_edit": "Add to the 'Domestic agenda and policy implementations' section under economic policies: In December 2025, President Trump surprised the public by announcing that tariffs could eliminate income taxes entirely, specifically aiming to end income taxes for Americans earning under $200,000 annually, funded by tariff revenue. Separately, he waived remaining fines against Southwest Airlines for its holiday meltdown via the Transportation Department under Secretary Sean Duffy.",
      "original_text": "In early December 2025, Trump stated that tariff revenues could be large enough to eventually replace federal income taxes, aligning with his protectionist agenda to promote domestic manufacturing. [223] [224]"
    },
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Keir_Starmer",
      "suggested_edit": "Add to the 'Scandals and Ethical Issues' section: In December 2025, controversy arose over the Nick Brown scandal, where Keir Starmer allegedly deliberately delayed the announcement of Nick Brown's suspension from the Labour Party, choosing 'a good day to bury bad news' and orchestrating a cover-up by refusing to disclose reasons, leading to accusations that Starmer is unfit to be Prime Minister.",
      "original_text": "Governance concerns escalated in September 2025 over the Labour Together funding scandal, where a resurfaced 2021 leaked email accused Starmer's chief of staff, Morgan McSweeney—former director of Labour Together—of concealing around £740,000 in undeclared donations from the Electoral Commission during an earlier investigation; these funds were funneled through the Labour Together organization to support Starmer's 2020 leadership bid and other party activities."
    }
